</article>


        
            
<article class="fyre-comment-article">
  <div class="fyre-comment-wrapper">
  
  
  
  <div class="fyre-comment-user">
    <a class="fyre-comment-author"><img src="http://gravatar.com/avatar/b1d0592c3385d70d9bfab4a720b9e283/?s=50&amp;d=http://avatars.fyre.co/a/anon/50.jpg" class=
    "fyre-user-avatar" alt="Murdo Ritchie" /></a>

    <div class="fyre-comment-socialsync fyre-comment-from-livefyre"></div>
  </div>
    
  <header class="fyre-comment-head">
    <a class="fyre-comment-username">Murdo Ritchie</a> 
    
    
    <span class="fyre-comment-user-rating" style="display: none;">5pts</span>
    <span class="fyre-comment-like" style="float: right;">
      
    </span>
    
  </header>
  
  <section class="fyre-comment-body">
    <div class="fyre-comment">
      <p><p>Interesting.  But you’ve only scratched the tip of the iceberg here.

You’re wrong to claim that the conflict in the Great Lakes region has been poorly reported.  There are more than enough news reports and books on this ongoing conflict to keep most people ware of its nature.

The problem is the unwillingness of British people to even acknowledge there’s a world beyond their own street corner.  Even the people who should have known better, including the committees against the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan gave me only blank looks when I mentioned the importance of this conflict.  Apparently, there wasn’t enough popular understand for it to be included.

Ironically, imperialism has been very busy in this region.  Despite a lot of talk about china encroaching on the west’s traditional preserve, western governments especially France have flown ALL of Africa’s leaders to special conferences to obtain favours.
Bizarrely, Britain has brought Mozambique into the Commonwealth –despite never having been part of the empire- and is trying to lever Francophone Rwanda in too.  Even though the French have an arrest warrant for the country’s leader Paul Kagame.  A major player in the regional wars.

Although it is a subject of interpretation when these wars began, some people date them from the the genocide in Rwanda in 1994.  Others choose different dates.
The Democratic Republic of Congo is believed to be the single richest part of the world with almost a monopoly of rare, unusual minerals.  The CIA wrote a report on this in the fifties outlining its strategic importance.  Since then, oil has also grown in importance.

I have little doubt that one of the secondary, but important reasons for the war on Libya was to weaken the African Union because Libya was one of the four or five main funders.

But I’m glad there are other people “out there” who are realising the significance of this region and conflict.  I look forward to reading more on this from you</p></p>
    </div>
    
  </section>

